BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:konior-research-assistant-ai-ukraine-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260710T074012Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260723
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260724
SUMMARY:Deadline: Paid Research Assistant: AI and the War in Ukraine
DESCRIPTION:Bogna Konior\, Assistant Professor of Media Theory at NYU Shang
 hai\, is hiring a paid research assistant for a project on Ukraine and art
 ificial intelligence. The work supports a forthcoming book with MIT Press\
 , plus an independent scenario she is writing on the future of AI with the
  war as a lens. WHAT THE WORK LOOKS LIKE: going month-by-month through new
 s archives (New York Times\, Reuters\, Financial Times\, and specialist ou
 tlets)\, annotating and cataloguing coverage of AI\, drones\, and autonomo
 us systems in the war\, plus other developments she will direct you to\; b
 uilding and maintaining a structured Notion database covering chronology\,
  companies\, industries\, and key actors\; and organizing and editing her 
 existing notes. WHO SHE IS LOOKING FOR: interest in and general knowledge 
 of AI\; prior research and annotation experience\, careful and detail-orie
 nted\, no sloppy citations\; comfortable with Notion and with AI tools\; U
 krainian language skill a strong plus (not required)\; familiarity with AI
 \, war\, tech\, and geopolitics news sources is great. Remote-friendly\, s
 tart ASAP. She will also consider people with no prior experience\, as wel
 l as current and previous students. TERMS: USD 18 per hour\, 10-15 hours p
 er week\, flexible schedule. TO APPLY: email bogna@nyu.edu with a short in
 troduction and background (link to website\, socials\, CV\, LinkedIn\, or 
 portfolio if you have one)\; where you are based and your weekly availabil
 ity\; and one recent AI-related story\, company\, or development you find 
 interesting and why (a vibe check). Bonus: a sample of past research or wr
 iting if you have it.\n\nOrganisation: Bogna Konior (NYU Shanghai)\nLocati
 on: Remote-friendly.\nAward: USD 18 per hour\; 10-15 hours per week\, flex
 ible schedule.\nDuration: Ongoing part-time research assistantship\; start
  as soon as possible.\n\nMore: https://www.instagram.com/p/Dak-bwACIMt/?ut
 m_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.instagram.com/p/Dak-bwACIMt/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugr
 antdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Remote-friendly.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:dedalus-foundation-senior-fellowship-2027@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260710T074012Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260915
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260916
SUMMARY:Deadline: Dedalus Foundation Senior Fellowship 2027
DESCRIPTION:The Dedalus Foundation\, established by artist Robert Motherwel
 l\, awards a Senior Fellowship supporting critical and historical studies 
 related to painting\, sculpture\, and allied arts of the twentieth century
 . The fellowship is open to art historians\, critics\, curators\, and othe
 r writers and scholars who have demonstrated their abilities through previ
 ous accomplishments. Awards provide a stipend of up to USD 30\,000 for pro
 jects lasting up to one year\, with the amount varying by project needs. A
 pplicants must be U.S. citizens and may not be currently pursuing academic
  degrees. Applications are submitted online and reference letters through 
 a separate form. A distinguished scholar jury selects recipients\, with aw
 ards announced by mid-December.\n\nOrganisation: The Dedalus Foundation\nL
 ocation: United States (remote\, project-based)\nAward: Stipend up to USD 
 30\,000\nDuration: Up to one year\n\nMore: https://dedalusfoundation.org/p
 rograms/fellowships-awards/view/senior-fellowship/?utm_source=artificialno
 uveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://dedalusfoundation.org/programs/fellowships-awards/view/senior-f
 ellowship/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:United States (remote\, project-based)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:justice-joy-summer-research-fellowship-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260710T074012Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260709
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260710
SUMMARY:Deadline: Justice + Joy Summer Research Fellowship 2026
DESCRIPTION:The Justice + Joy Research Fellowship is a seven-week virtual s
 ummer program for girls\, young women\, and gender-expansive young people 
 of color (ages 18-26) in the United States who want to explore issues impa
 cting their lives\, communities\, and futures. Fellows identify a topic th
 ey care about\, such as mental health\, education\, reproductive justice\,
  immigration\, AI and technology\, gender-based violence\, beauty standard
 s\, young parenthood\, or another issue affecting their communities\, and 
 develop an original research project grounded in their experiences\, quest
 ions\, and ideas. Throughout the summer\, fellows participate in weekly vi
 rtual sessions\, engage with guest speakers\, build community with peers f
 rom across the country\, and receive mentorship and support as they develo
 p their research. The fellowship culminates in a capstone showcase where f
 ellows present their work to the Justice + Joy community\, including organ
 izational leaders\, partners\, and supporters. No prior research experienc
 e is required\; the program seeks young people who are curious\, committed
  to learning\, and interested in using research as a tool for understandin
 g\, advocacy\, and change. COMMITMENT: weekly virtual sessions on Wednesda
 ys 5:00-6:30 PM ET (9 July - 20 August 2026)\; approximately 2-4 hours of 
 independent work per week\; required orientation on Wednesday 9 July\; dev
 elopment of an individual research proposal or conceptual framework\; pres
 entation at the capstone showcase (tentatively in person\, mid-September 2
 026\, with all travel and lodging covered). WHAT YOU GET: a USD 2\,000 sti
 pend paid upon successful completion\; skills-based training in research m
 ethods\, social justice frameworks\, and community advocacy\; guest speake
 r sessions\; a peer community\; and a real audience for the research (the 
 Justice + Joy board and funders). Apply via the Google Form. Note: an expl
 icit application deadline is not stated\; the required orientation and pro
 gram start is 9 July 2026\, so apply before then.\n\nOrganisation: Justice
  + Joy\nLocation: United States\; fully virtual program. Capstone showcase
  tentatively in person (mid-September 2026)\, with travel and lodging cove
 red.\nAward: USD 2\,000 stipend paid upon successful program completion\, 
 plus skills-based training\, guest speaker sessions\, and peer community. 
 All travel and lodging for the in-person capstone are covered.\nDuration: 
 Seven-week virtual program\, 9 July to 20 August 2026\, with a capstone sh
 owcase mid-September 2026. Weekly Wednesday sessions 5:00-6:30 PM ET plus 
 approximately 2-4 hours of independent work per week.\n\nMore: https://doc
 s.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSfXN_oqSA7G7RRPjhLp-_McFix70m4g8Q_yny0aiBDb-
 qfHvw/viewform?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSfXN_oqSA7G7RRPjhLp-_McFix70m4
 g8Q_yny0aiBDb-qfHvw/viewform?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_med
 ium=referral
LOCATION:United States\; fully virtual program. Capstone showcase tentative
 ly in person (mid-September 2026)\, with travel and lodging covered.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:ddc-trygfonden-fellowship-2027@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260710T074012Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260901
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260902
SUMMARY:Deadline: Digital Democracy Centre x TrygFonden Fellowship Program 
 2027
DESCRIPTION:The Digital Democracy Centre (DDC) at the University of Souther
 n Denmark\, with support from TrygFonden\, is calling for applications for
  its 2027 fellowship cohort. The program fosters collaboration between res
 earchers\, journalists\, and policymakers exploring the impact of digital 
 technology and AI on media\, politics\, and democracy. Fellows collaborate
  with a self-selected DDC mentor to generate new knowledge\, contribute to
  public debate\, develop networks\, and produce tangible outreach outputs 
 such as policy briefs\, educational packages\, and talks. THREE FELLOWSHIP
  TYPES: (1) academic fellows researching digital technologies and democrac
 y\; (2) journalist fellows covering digital technology and democracy\; (3)
  policy fellows contributing to the regulatory debate. Target group: resea
 rchers\, journalism graduates\, and policymakers in research/educational i
 nstitutions\, media organizations\, ministries\, NGOs\, etc. PRIORITIES: p
 rojects with clear relevance to Denmark or Danish society (including compa
 rative/international projects yielding insights relevant to a Danish conte
 xt)\; in 2027\, projects related to DDC's Hybrid Warfare Initiative (socie
 tal resilience to new forms of international conflict\, with a focus on di
 gital technologies and AI) are also prioritized. EXPECTATIONS: applicants 
 must secure confirmation of mentorship from their desired DDC mentor BEFOR
 E applying (applications without a confirmed mentor are automatically reje
 cted\; PhD students and research assistants are generally not eligible as 
 mentors\, and Sten Schaumburg-Muller is unavailable as a mentor for the 20
 27 call)\; applicants must also coordinate support from their current supe
 rvisors/managers. Fellows engage in DDC activities\, seminars/workshops\, 
 and public outreach\, and submit a short report within two months of finis
 hing. APPLICATION (in English): preliminary project title\, fellowship typ
 e\, brief project description (max 1000 chars)\, detailed description and 
 timeline (max 2400 chars\, including duration\, confirmed mentor\, and rem
 ote/in-office work plan)\, description of activities and collaboration wit
 h external practice partners (max 1000 chars)\, expected product/impact/ou
 tput (max 500 chars)\, a CV (max 5 pages)\, and an overview of the posts f
 or which financial support is sought. Submit the application form (PDF or 
 Word) plus CV as PDFs to ddc@sdu.dk with subject line 'DDC / TrygFonden Fe
 llowship application'. Deadline 1 September 2026\; decisions communicated 
 no later than 1 October 2026.\n\nOrganisation: Digital Democracy Centre (U
 niversity of Southern Denmark)\, with support from TrygFonden\nLocation: O
 dense\, Denmark (University of Southern Denmark). Flexible mix of in-offic
 e stays at the DDC in Odense and remote periods\; stays planned to the Dan
 ish working calendar.\nAward: Either a salary subsidy or a stipend to help
  with travel and/or housing\; specific benefits (financial support\, acces
 s to DDC research resources\, flexible working spaces\, speaker series\, n
 etworks) vary by agreement between the fellow\, DDC\, and partnering organ
 izations. Applicants describe the posts they seek support for (flights\, h
 ousing\, research costs\, salary compensation\, stipend\, etc.).\nDuration
 : Flexible\; typically 2-6 months (minimum two months\, can include shorte
 r DDC stays and remote periods)\, longer in exceptional cases. Fellowships
  start anywhere in 2027.\n\nMore: https://www.sdu.dk/en/forskning/forsknin
 gsenheder/samf/digitaldemocracycentre/news+folder/ddcxtrygfonden-fellowshi
 p-call-2027?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.sdu.dk/en/forskning/forskningsenheder/samf/digitaldemocracy
 centre/news+folder/ddcxtrygfonden-fellowship-call-2027?utm_source=artifici
 alnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Odense\, Denmark (University of Southern Denmark). Flexible mix of
  in-office stays at the DDC in Odense and remote periods\; stays planned t
 o the Danish working calendar.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:gmu-civic-science-fellow-science-policy-collaborative-2026@artificialno
 uveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260710T074012Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260705
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260706
SUMMARY:Deadline: Civic Science Postdoctoral Fellow: Science Policy Collabo
 rative (George Mason University) 2026
DESCRIPTION:A grant-funded\, full-time Civic Science Postdoctoral Fellowshi
 p supporting the Science Policy Collaborative\, a national network that st
 rengthens the development\, sustainability and evaluation of U.S. science 
 policy programs. The fellow helps shape an emerging field at the heart of 
 a growing community of practice connecting science policy programs across 
 the country. WHAT YOU'LL DO: conduct a national needs assessment of U.S. s
 cience policy programs and publish the findings\; support the Collaborativ
 e's working groups by scoping deliverables and building partnerships to ex
 ecute them\; develop infrastructure for knowledge exchange (tools like log
 ic models and evaluation frameworks)\; connect programs with national and 
 international experts on the use of research evidence (URE) and evidence-i
 nformed policymaking\; present at partner meetings and convenings\; and re
 ceive mentorship from George Mason University\, UC Riverside and other lea
 ders of the Collaborative. WHO THEY'RE LOOKING FOR: someone with a doctora
 l degree\, relevant experience\, knowledge of science-for-policy programs\
 , and skills in network coordination\, needs assessment or program evaluat
 ion\, and writing for broad audiences (see the posting for exact criteria)
 . Fairfax\, VA (hybrid eligible)\; full-time 18-month postdoctoral appoint
 ment issued as two contracts (12 months plus 6 months)\; salary about USD 
 80\,000/year plus benefits. APPLY with a cover letter\, CV\, three referen
 ces and a writing sample written for broad audiences\; for full considerat
 ion apply by 5 July 2026 (open until filled). Questions to search coordina
 tor Natalie V Lapidot-Croitoru\, nlapidot@gmu.edu.\n\nOrganisation: George
  Mason University (with UC Riverside)\, via the Science Policy Collaborati
 ve and Civic Science Fellows network\nLocation: Fairfax\, Virginia\, USA (
 hybrid eligible).\nAward: Salary approximately USD 80\,000 per year plus b
 enefits. No application fee.\nDuration: 18-month postdoctoral appointment 
 (two contracts: 12 months + 6 months)\n\nMore: https://listings.jobs.gmu.e
 du/jobs/civic-science-fellow-science-policy-collaborative-fairfax-va-virgi
 nia-united-states-other?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=r
 eferral
URL:https://listings.jobs.gmu.edu/jobs/civic-science-fellow-science-policy-
 collaborative-fairfax-va-virginia-united-states-other?utm_source=artificia
 lnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Fairfax\, Virginia\, USA (hybrid eligible).
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:aria-future-proofing-climate-weather-opportunity-seeds-2026@artificialn
 ouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260710T074012Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260731
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260801
SUMMARY:Deadline: ARIA: Future Proofing Our Climate and Weather (Opportunit
 y Seeds) 2026
DESCRIPTION:ARIA is seeking proposals for opportunity seeds\, funding of up
  to GBP 500\,000 for early-stage research that explores new pathways for c
 limate adaptation and resilience. Decarbonisation is the only sustainable 
 route out of the climate crisis\, but environmental changes are outpacing 
 current mitigation efforts\, and if an abrupt alteration in a climate syst
 em were to unfold we would have no tools to mitigate the effects\; scienti
 fic\, engineering and social science research could provide practical and 
 responsible intervention and adaptation options. WHAT THEY ARE LOOKING FOR
 : ideas ranging from early-stage\, curiosity-driven research through to ad
 vanced translational science. Specific areas of interest include\, but are
  not limited to: carbon dioxide removal (novel concepts to accelerate the 
 drawdown of atmospheric carbon)\; extreme weather forecasting (breakthroug
 hs in predicting extreme weather events to better prepare vulnerable syste
 ms)\; and new ideas related to solar geoengineering\, strictly excluding p
 roposals specifically designed to investigate altering the Earth's surface
  temperature by affecting planetary albedo\, incoming solar radiation\, or
  the atmosphere's emissivity (the core focus of the main Exploring Climate
  Cooling\, ECC\, programme). OUT OF SCOPE: ideas that squarely fit within 
 the ECC programme\; emissions reduction projects and improvements to the e
 nergy efficiency of buildings or vehicles\; and commercial products or res
 earch likely to be funded by traditional venture capital or grants. CONSTR
 AINTS: any proposal for outdoor experiments must demonstrate conformity to
  ARIA's governance framework for outdoor experiments\, and all successful 
 applicants must sign ARIA's Intellectual Property Pledge to ensure finding
 s are accessible for the public good. Application deadline: 31 July 2026\,
  14:00 BST.\n\nOrganisation: ARIA (Advanced Research and Invention Agency)
 \nLocation: UK-based funder (ARIA)\; proposals welcome across scientific\,
  engineering and social science research.\nAward: Opportunity seeds of up 
 to GBP 500\,000 for early-stage research. No application fee.\nDuration: E
 arly-stage research projects (project length set by the proposal)\n\nMore:
  https://aria.org.uk/opportunity-spaces/future-proofing-our-climate-and-we
 ather/opportunity-seeds?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=r
 eferral
URL:https://aria.org.uk/opportunity-spaces/future-proofing-our-climate-and-
 weather/opportunity-seeds?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium
 =referral
LOCATION:UK-based funder (ARIA)\; proposals welcome across scientific\, eng
 ineering and social science research.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:spencer-foundation-vision-grants-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260710T074012Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260812
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260813
SUMMARY:Deadline: Spencer Foundation: Vision Grants 2026 (Research Planning
  Grants)
DESCRIPTION:Vision Grants are research planning grants that give scholars a
 nd their collaborators the time\, space\, resources and support to plan a 
 large-scale study or program of research focused on transforming education
  systems toward greater equity. Rather than a fully fleshed-out research p
 lan\, the proposal is an invitation to think forward about what research i
 s needed to transform education systems toward equity and how that systems
  change will happen\, identifying the system(s) targeted and the specific 
 levers the team thinks must be engaged. Grants bring together a team for 1
 2 to 18 months to collaboratively develop ambitious\, large-scale\, cross-
 disciplinary research projects co-designed with practitioners\, policymake
 rs\, communities and other partners. Awarded teams also join a cohort lear
 ning program held in person in Chicago. ELIGIBILITY: PIs and Co-PIs must h
 ave appropriate experience or an earned doctorate in an academic disciplin
 e or a terminal degree in a professional field\; graduate students may be 
 on the team but cannot be PI or Co-PI. The PI must be affiliated with a no
 n-profit or public/governmental institution willing to serve as the admini
 stering organization (colleges\, universities\, school districts\, researc
 h facilities\, or other 501(c)(3) non-profits\, or non-US equivalents)\; t
 he Spencer Foundation does not award grants directly to individuals. Open 
 to applicants in the US and internationally\; proposals in English\, budge
 ts in USD. PIs and Co-PIs may apply even with another active Spencer grant
  or proposal in review\, but may not be part of more than one Vision Grant
  proposal. Note: a Vision Grant is a prerequisite for applying to Spencer'
 s Transformative Research Grant program (TRG\, USD 3.5 million)\, though r
 eceiving one does not guarantee a TRG. PROCESS: applications opened 4 June
  2026. A required Intent to Apply form (max 200 words\, non-binding) is du
 e 12 August 2026 at 12:00 PM noon Central time\; the Full Proposal (2000-w
 ord narrative) is due 16 September 2026 at 12:00 PM noon Central time. Pro
 gram contact: Jasmine Knetl\, visiongrants@spencer.org.\n\nOrganisation: S
 pencer Foundation\nLocation: Worldwide\; PI must be affiliated with a non-
 profit or public/governmental institution (US 501(c)(3) or non-US equivale
 nt) that will serve as the administering organization. Proposals accepted 
 from the US and internationally\; English only\; budgets in US Dollars.\nA
 ward: USD 75\,000 total per grant\; no indirect cost charges permitted. No
  application fee.\nDuration: 12 to 18 months (research planning grant)\n\n
 More: https://www.spencer.org/grant_types/vision-grants?utm_source=artific
 ialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.spencer.org/grant_types/vision-grants?utm_source=artificial
 nouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Worldwide\; PI must be affiliated with a non-profit or public/gove
 rnmental institution (US 501(c)(3) or non-US equivalent) that will serve a
 s the administering organization. Proposals accepted from the US and inter
 nationally\; English only\; budgets in US Dollars.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:biswas-family-foundation-fast-grants-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260710T074012Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260615
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260616
SUMMARY:Deadline: Biswas Family Foundation: Fast Grants Program 2026 (Sprin
 g Cycle)
DESCRIPTION:Fast Grants fund high-ambition\, curiosity-driven pilot project
 s at the intersection of AI and health\, for early-career scientists or es
 tablished researchers pivoting into the field. THEMES: training\, fine-tun
 ing or evaluating models on biomedical data\; exploring or assembling data
 sets that could unlock new clinical or biological insight\; building AI to
 ols or agents that scale a scientist's leverage\; pilot experiments that d
 e-risk a bigger funding ask\; and anything else where modest\, fast capita
 l meaningfully accelerates an AI- or data-driven path to a health breakthr
 ough. ELIGIBILITY: researchers at any career stage including early-career 
 faculty\, postdocs\, graduate students\, and undergraduates (with faculty 
 sponsorship\; USD 25K tier only). Applicants must be affiliated with an in
 stitution eligible to receive US charitable gifts. Open worldwide. FUNDING
 : three tiers (USD 25K / 50K / 100K) with a single payment\, 12-month peri
 od\, indirect costs capped at 15 percent. APPLY: submit a concise applicat
 ion (bullet points\, ~300 words max) through the online form\; decisions a
 re based on the written application alone\, with no interview round. Deadl
 ine for Cycle 1: 15 June 2026\, 11:59pm PT (a second cycle closes 15 Decem
 ber 2026).\n\nOrganisation: Biswas Family Foundation\nLocation: Worldwide\
 ; applicant must be affiliated with an institution eligible to receive US 
 charitable gifts (US 501(c)(3) public charity\, government instrumentality
 \, or a confirmed non-US equivalent / US fiscal sponsor)\nAward: USD 25\,0
 00 (20 projects)\, USD 50\,000 (10 projects) or USD 100\,000 (5 projects)\
 ; single payment\, 12-month project period\, indirect costs capped at 15 p
 ercent. No application fee.\nDuration: 12-month project period\n\nMore: ht
 tps://www.biswasfamilyfoundation.org/science/fast-grants?utm_source=artifi
 cialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.biswasfamilyfoundation.org/science/fast-grants?utm_source=a
 rtificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Worldwide\; applicant must be affiliated with an institution eligi
 ble to receive US charitable gifts (US 501(c)(3) public charity\, governme
 nt instrumentality\, or a confirmed non-US equivalent / US fiscal sponsor)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:arua-early-career-research-fellowships-2026-option2@artificialnouveau.g
 ithub.io
DTSTAMP:20260710T074012Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260715
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260716
SUMMARY:Deadline: ARUA: Early-Career Research Fellowships 2026 (Option 2)
DESCRIPTION:An Early-Career Research Fellowship program funding up to 42 ea
 rly-career researchers to conduct globally competitive research at the hos
 t and affiliated institutions of ARUA's 13 Centres of Excellence and the 2
 2 Africa-Europe Clusters of Excellence. ELIGIBILITY: early-career research
 ers no older than 35 at the time of application\; at least 70 percent of f
 ellowships are reserved for female candidates. STRUCTURE: each fellowship 
 lasts six months\; Option 2 runs September 2026 to February 2027 (Option 1
 \, March to August 2026\, has closed). SUPPORT: monthly stipend of USD 2\,
 000\, a modest accommodation payment\, and travel support (return ticket t
 o the host institution)\; successful candidates are contracted by ARUA for
  six months. Deadline for Option 2: 15 July 2026.\n\nOrganisation: African
  Research Universities Alliance (ARUA)\, with the Mastercard Foundation an
 d Carnegie Corporation of New York\nLocation: Host and affiliated institut
 ions of ARUA's Centres of Excellence and Africa-Europe Clusters of Excelle
 nce\; for African early-career researchers\nAward: Monthly stipend of USD 
 2\,000\, a modest accommodation payment\, and travel support (return ticke
 t to host institution). 6-month fellowship.\nDuration: 6 months (Option 2:
  September 2026 to February 2027)\n\nMore: https://arua.org/early-career-r
 esearch-fellowships/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=refe
 rral
URL:https://arua.org/early-career-research-fellowships/?utm_source=artifici
 alnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Host and affiliated institutions of ARUA's Centres of Excellence a
 nd Africa-Europe Clusters of Excellence\; for African early-career researc
 hers
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:cambridge-africa-alborada-research-fund-2026@artificialnouveau.github.i
 o
DTSTAMP:20260710T074012Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260903
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260904
SUMMARY:Deadline: Cambridge-Africa: ALBORADA Research Fund 2026
DESCRIPTION:The Cambridge-Africa ALBORADA Research Fund competitively award
 s grants to pairs of researchers\, one from an African university or resea
 rch institution and one from the University of Cambridge or an allied rese
 arch institute\, across all disciplines\, to initiate and/or strengthen re
 search collaborations. ELIGIBILITY: both applicants must be at post-doctor
 al level or above\, with employment contracts extending beyond the award e
 nd date\, and apply with the support of their Head of Department or equiva
 lent\; the Cambridge applicant must work at the University of Cambridge or
  an affiliated institute (Wellcome Sanger Institute\, NIAB\, British Antar
 ctic Survey)\; the African applicant must be based at an African universit
 y or equivalent. Limited student support is considered where it enhances t
 he Cambridge-Africa relationship. FUNDING: GBP 1\,000 to 25\,000\, coverin
 g research costs including reagents\, fieldwork\, equipment and research-t
 raining activities in Africa. APPLY: the Cambridge-based applicant registe
 rs using an institutional email (cam.ac.uk\, sanger.ac.uk\, babraham.ac.uk
 \, bas.ac.uk or niab.com) and invites the Africa-based applicant via the o
 nline form. Deadline: 3 September 2026. Queries: alboradafund@cambridge-af
 rica.cam.ac.uk.\n\nOrganisation: Cambridge-Africa Programme\, University o
 f Cambridge (supported by The ALBORADA Trust)\nLocation: Pairs of research
 ers: one at the University of Cambridge or an allied institute (Wellcome S
 anger Institute\, NIAB\, British Antarctic Survey)\, one at an African uni
 versity or research institution\nAward: Competitive grants of GBP 1\,000 t
 o 25\,000. Covers research costs such as reagents\, fieldwork\, equipment 
 and research-training activities in Africa (e.g. setting up courses/worksh
 ops). No application fee.\nDuration: Short collaborative research projects
 \n\nMore: https://www.cambridge-africa.cam.ac.uk/initiatives/2026-call-for
 -applications?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.cambridge-africa.cam.ac.uk/initiatives/2026-call-for-applic
 ations?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Pairs of researchers: one at the University of Cambridge or an all
 ied institute (Wellcome Sanger Institute\, NIAB\, British Antarctic Survey
 )\, one at an African university or research institution
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:ioc-osc-phd-early-career-research-grant-2027@artificialnouveau.github.i
 o
DTSTAMP:20260710T074012Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260922
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260923
SUMMARY:Deadline: IOC Olympic Studies Centre: PhD Students and Early Career
  Academics Research Grant Programme 2027
DESCRIPTION:The IOC Olympic Studies Centre supports PhD students and early-
 career academics conducting scholarly research on the Olympic Movement\, i
 ts history and ideals\, the athletes\, the Olympic Games and their impact 
 on contemporary society and culture. ELIGIBILITY: current postgraduate stu
 dents enrolled in a PhD programme within the human and/or social sciences\
 , with Olympism\, the Olympic Movement or the Olympic Games as at least on
 e research focus\; also academic staff and postdoctoral fellows who comple
 ted their doctorate (or equivalent highest degree) in or after 2024. AWARD
 : up to USD 6\,000. APPLY: application files and related correspondence mu
 st reach the OSC before Tuesday 22 September 2026\; see the programme rule
 s and application form on the IOC Olympic Studies Centre website.\n\nOrgan
 isation: International Olympic Committee\, Olympic Studies Centre\nLocatio
 n: Worldwide\; research on Olympism\, the Olympic Movement and the Olympic
  Games within the human and social sciences\nAward: Research grant of up t
 o USD 6\,000. No application fee.\nDuration: Research project (grant perio
 d per programme rules)\n\nMore: https://www.olympics.com/ioc/olympic-studi
 es-centre/research-grant-programmes?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&
 utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.olympics.com/ioc/olympic-studies-centre/research-grant-prog
 rammes?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Worldwide\; research on Olympism\, the Olympic Movement and the Ol
 ympic Games within the human and social sciences
