BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:european-commission-born-digital-heritage-2026@artificialnouveau.github
 .io
DTSTAMP:20260710T074012Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260716
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260717
SUMMARY:Deadline: European Commission: Safeguarding Europe's Born-Digital H
 eritage (PPPA-2026-BORN-DIGITAL)
DESCRIPTION:The European Commission is offering a single grant of up to €
 1\,985\,000 (85% co-financing) for a project focused on safeguarding born-
 digital cultural heritage across EU member states. Scope includes: assessi
 ng the preservation state of born-digital art\, web archives\, video games
 \, and digital content created outside cultural institutions\; mapping EU 
 and national legal frameworks\; identifying non-legislative barriers (tech
 nical\, financial\, organisational\, cultural)\; and providing guidance on
  creating preservation copies of licensed or legally accessible materials.
  This is a scoping and advocacy project\, not a digitisation grant. ELIGIB
 ILITY: the application must be led by a consortium of at least 5 independe
 nt entities from 5 different EU countries\, which rules out solo applicant
 s and single-country organisations. Grant reference: PPPA-2026-BORN-DIGITA
 L. Deadline: 16 July 2026. Verify the current deadline at ec.europa.eu bef
 ore applying (one secondary source listed 1 June 2026\; the primary call-f
 iche PDF and the Cyprus government funding portal both confirm 16 July 202
 6).\n\nOrganisation: European Commission (Pilot Projects and Preparatory A
 ctions\, Culture strand)\nLocation: European Union. Consortium of at least
  5 independent entities from 5 different EU member states required.\nAward
 : Up to €1\,985\,000\, covering up to 85% of eligible project costs (15%
  co-financing required). No application fee.\nDuration: Project duration t
 o be defined in the proposal\; covers a scoping and mapping phase across E
 U member states.\n\nMore: https://ec.europa.eu/info/funding-tenders/opport
 unities/docs/2021-2027/pppa/wp-call/2026/call-fiche_pppa-2026-born-digital
 _en.pdf?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://ec.europa.eu/info/funding-tenders/opportunities/docs/2021-2027/
 pppa/wp-call/2026/call-fiche_pppa-2026-born-digital_en.pdf?utm_source=arti
 ficialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:European Union. Consortium of at least 5 independent entities from
  5 different EU member states required.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:neh-collections-stewardship-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260710T074012Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20261215
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20261216
SUMMARY:Deadline: NEH: Collections Stewardship (December 2026 cycle)
DESCRIPTION:NEH Collections Stewardship funds preservation projects at libr
 aries\, archives\, museums\, colleges/universities\, and preservation-serv
 ices organisations. Eligible activities include digitisation and reformatt
 ing of collections for public access through digital repositories\, preser
 vation planning\, and environmental assessments. Relevant for organisation
 s working with born-digital or digitally reformatted collections including
  software\, AI artefacts\, and digital cultural heritage. Applications for
  the December 2026 cycle open 31 August 2026\; deadline 15 December 2026. 
 A May 2026 cycle has already passed. ELIGIBILITY: institutional applicants
  only (libraries\, archives\, museums\, colleges\, universities\, preserva
 tion-services organisations based in the US)\; individual researchers and 
 for-profit entities are not eligible. Apply via grants.gov.\n\nOrganisatio
 n: National Endowment for the Humanities (NEH)\nLocation: United States. A
 pplicants must be US-based institutions.\nAward: Up to $350\,000 for singl
 e organizations\; up to $500\,000 for consortia. Projects up to 3 years. N
 o application fee.\nDuration: Up to 3 years.\n\nMore: https://www.neh.gov/
 program/collections-stewardship?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_
 medium=referral
URL:https://www.neh.gov/program/collections-stewardship?utm_source=artifici
 alnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:United States. Applicants must be US-based institutions.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:kb-researcher-in-residence-2027@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260710T074012Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260927
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260928
SUMMARY:Deadline: KB Researcher-in-Residence (RiR) 2027
DESCRIPTION:ELIGIBILITY: two Researcher-in-Residence positions in 2027. Ope
 n to early-career researchers of any discipline (data science\, social sci
 ence\, computer science\, humanities) who are currently working on a PhD o
 r within 5 years of their PhD end date. You must have\, or be able to secu
 re\, an affiliation with a Dutch university or research institute willing 
 to second you\; external PhD students may use the funding to obtain such a
  contract. Your project must make use of one or more of the KB digital col
 lections and you must be able to work with primarily Dutch data. You must 
 be available at 0.5 FTE over 6 months and able to spend two days a week on
 -site at the KB in The Hague. COLLECTIONS: over 130 million digitized page
 s of newspapers\, magazines\, radio bulletins and books from 1470 onward (
 via Delpher and DBNL)\, a born-digital web collection of more than 23\,000
  websites\, ground-truth and derived datasets on the KB Lab\, and metadata
  including Linked Data. APPLY: use the official proposal template and subm
 it a single PDF by 27 September 2026 to dh@kb.nl\, after reading the call'
 s terms and conditions\; questions to dh@kb.nl. TIMELINE: deadline 27 Sept
 ember 2026\; internal eligibility review followed by an external committee
  review\; outcome notified November 2026\; residencies start Q1 and Q3 202
 7. DISCIPLINES: digital humanities / data science / computational research
  with cultural-heritage collections. NOTE: the output is usually a dataset
  or tool prototype hosted on the KB Lab\; you agree to share results via b
 log posts on the KB Lab and to publish resulting tools or data under an op
 en license within 6 months of the residency. Proposals should align with t
 he KB Research Agenda or the Cultural AI Lab.\n\nOrganisation: KB\, Nation
 al Library of the Netherlands\nLocation: The Hague\, Netherlands (two days
  per week on-site at the KB premises)\nAward: Secondment at 0.5 FTE for 6 
 months based on your current salary\, up to EUR 5\,590 gross per month for
  a full-time-equivalent position\, plus travel expenses\, office facilitie
 s\, and support from a research software engineer\, research advisor\, and
  collection and data specialists. No application fee.\nDuration: 6 months 
 at 0.5 FTE (two days per week on-site)\; two positions in 2027\, starting 
 Q1 and Q3\n\nMore: https://lab.kb.nl/news/call-kb-researcher-residence-rir
 -2027?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://lab.kb.nl/news/call-kb-researcher-residence-rir-2027?utm_source
 =artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:The Hague\, Netherlands (two days per week on-site at the KB premi
 ses)
END:VEVENT
